Asymptotic Analysis:-

Asymptotic Analysis is a way to measure how efficient an algorithm is.

It tells us how the running time or memory usage changes when the input size becomes very large (n increases).

Instead of checking the exact time in seconds, we study the growth rate of the algorithm.

Why do we use Asymptotic Analysis?
To compare different algorithms.
To know which algorithm performs better for large inputs.
It does not depend on the computer, programming language, or hardware.
It focuses on the algorithm's efficiency.


Example

Suppose we have two algorithms.

Algorithm A

Takes 5n + 10 operations.

Algorithm B

Takes n² + 2 operations.

For small values of n, both may look similar.

But when n becomes very large:

5n grows slowly.
n² grows much faster.

So, Algorithm A is more efficient.

Types of Asymptotic Notations

There are three main notations.

1. Big O Notation (O)

Big O tells us the maximum time an algorithm can take.

It is also called the Worst Case.

Example

Searching for a number in an unsorted array.

If the number is at the last position, we check every element.

Time Complexity:

O(n)

Example:

Array = [5, 9, 2, 7, 1]

Find 1

We check:
5
9
2
7
1

Total = 5 comparisons

Worst Case = O(n)




2. Omega Notation (Ω)

Omega tells us the minimum time an algorithm can take.

It is also called the Best Case.

Example

If the required number is at the first position.

Array = [5, 9, 2, 7, 1]

Find 5

Only one comparison is needed.

Time Complexity:

Ω(1)





3. Theta Notation (Θ)

Theta tells us the average or exact growth of an algorithm.

It gives both the upper and lower limits.

Example:

Θ(n)

means the algorithm usually grows linearly.
